definition.value: Conjugate base of 3,4,5-trimethoxycinnamic acid.
Any fatty acid anion with a chain length greater than C22.
Any fatty acid anion obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxy group of a short-chain fatty acid (chain length of less than C6).
Any fatty acid anion in which there is no C-C unsaturation.
Any saturated fatty acid anion lacking a carbon side-chain.
Any fatty acid anion with a carbon side-chain or isopropyl termination.
Any saturated fatty acid anion with a carbon side-chain or isopropyl termination.
An organic anion of general formula RS(=O)2O(-) where R is an organyl group.
A penicillin in which the substituent at position 6 of the penam ring is a (2R)-2-amino-2-(cyclohexa-1,4-dien-1-yl)acetamido group.
A tripeptide consisting of betaAlaGlyGly with a 4-hydroxy-3-iodo-5-nitrophenylacetyl substituent on the beta-alanine nitrogen.
An azide carrying a (4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.
The conjugate base of 3,4,5-trimethoxybenzoic acid.
The monohydrate of (+)-catechin.
A carbapenemcarboxylic acid having a 2-(acetamidovinyl)sulfanyl group at the 2-position and an (S)-1-hydroxyethyl group at the 6-position.
A penicillanic acid having a (6R)-formamido substituent.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 6-formamidopenicillanic acid, formed by proton loss from the carboxy group.

A tetracycline-based broad-spectrum antibiotic. It is approximately 5000 times more soluble than tetracycline base and is unique amongst tetracyclines in that it is absorbed by the "active transport" process across the intestinal wall.
A butanone derivative having two hydroxy substituents at the 1-position and an ethoxy substituent at the 3-position.

Polymyxins are antibiotics with a general structure consisting of a cyclic peptide with a long hydrophobic tail. They disrupt the structure of the bacterial cell membrane by interacting with its phospholipids. Polymyxins are produced by the Gram-positive bacterium Bacillus polymyxa and are selectively toxic for Gram-negative bacteria.
A polymyxin having a 6-methylheptanoyl group at the amino terminus.
A polymyxin having a (6R)-6-methyloctanoyl group at the amino terminus.
Conjugate base of 2-cyanocinnamic acid.
Conjugate base of 5-chlorosalicylic acid.
A substance used as an indicator  of a biological state.

The dihydrate of the disodium salt of balsalazide. A prodrug, releasing the anti-inflammatory 5-aminosalicylic acid (mesalazine) in the large intestine, it is used in the treatment of ulcerative colitis.
Nonaethylene glycol in which one of the hydroxy groups is substituted by methoxy.
The sesquihydrate of the sodium salt of bromfenac. It is used for the management of ocular pain and treatment of postoperative inflammation in patients who have undergone cataract extraction.
A pyrrole-2,5-dicarboxylic acid having 7-chloroindol-3-yl groups at the 3- and 4-positions.
A pyrrole compound having two carboxy substituents at any position on the ring.
The monohydrate of calcium acetate.
Any fatty acid whose skeletal carbon atoms form an unbranched open chain.
A fatty acid anion formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid functional group of a straight-chain fatty acid.

A third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic with [(1-methyl-1H-tetrazol-5-yl)sulfanyl]methyl and (R)-2-{[(4-hydroxy-6-methylpyridin-3-yl)carbonyl]amino}-2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetamido groups at positions 3 and 7, respectively, of the cephem skeleton. It has a broad spectrum of antibacterial activity.
Any fatty acid containing anywhere in its structure a ring of atoms.
A lipid-based glycol consisting of (3S,4R)-3-methoxy-4-methylnonacosane having (9R)- and (11S)-hydroxy substituents; a characteristic constituent of the waxes of tubercule bacilli.
An amido disaccharide fragment which mimicks the terminus of the O-polysaccharide of Vibrio cholerae O:1, serotype Ogawa.
The methyl glycoside of L-xylopyranose.
The pyranose form of L-xylose.
A galactose phosphate consisting of N-acetyl-D-galactosamine having a choline phosphate group at the 6-position.
The hydrochloride formed from methylamine.
The conjugate acid of methylamine; major species at pH 7.3.

A broad spectrum, third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic with (Z)-2-(4-methyl-1,3-thiazol-5-yl)ethenyl and (2Z)-2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetamido groups at positions 3 and 7, respectively, of the cephem skeleton. Generally administered as its orally absorbed pivaloyloxymethyl ester prodrug, it is used for the treatment of mild to moderate infections caused by susceptible strains of microorganisms in acute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis, community-acquired pneumonia, pharyngitis/tonsillitis, and uncomplicated skin and skin-structure infections.
L-cysteine substituted at sulfur by a 2-boronoethyl group.
The conjugate acid of cefepime.

3H-2,1-Benzoxathiole 1,1-dioxide in which both of the hydrogens at position 3 have been substituted by 3,5-dibromo-4-hydroxyphenyl groups. It is used as a laboratory indicator, changing from yellow below pH 3 to purple at pH 4.6, and as a size marker for monitoring the progress of agarose gel and polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis. It has also been used as an industrial dye.
4-Aminobenzoic acid in which one of the hydrogens ortho- to the carboxylic acid group is substituted by chlorine.
A monosaccharide derivative that is a D-glucose derivative having an acyl group at the O-6 position.
The (R)-enantiomer of chlorphenesin.
The (S)-enantiomer of chlorphenesin.
The dihydrate of the anhydrous form of cidofovir. A nucleoside analogue, it is an injectable antiviral used for the treatment of cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis in AIDS patients.
